[Bewick's swan belongs to the species _Cygnus columbianus_ (tundra swan), subspecies _Cygnus columbianus bewickii_ (http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/accounts/Cygnus_columbianus_bewickii/classification/#Cygnus_columbianus_bewickii).

"The Bewick's swans are commonly found in the Palaearctic habitat zone which includes many places in Asia, Europe, northern Africa and the Arabian Peninsula.

"The Bewick swans spend their breeding seasons in coastal lowlands of Siberia and in September they fly to the wintering grounds. Birds living near the Taimyr Peninsula normally winter in the British Isles, in Denmark and in the Netherlands. Birds living in eastern Russia migrate through Mongolia in the coastal regions of Japan, Korea and southern China as well as in Taiwan."
(http://www.animalspot.net/tundra-swan.html#Sub-species)

Pictures of _Cygnus columbianus bewickii_ can be seen at http://www.arkive.org/bewicks-swan/cygnus-columbianus-bewickii/.

Subscribers may also refer to the comments made by Mod.AS in ProMED-mail post 20140417.2412249: "The role of migratory birds in the current HPAI H5N8 epizootic has already become (similarly to previous HPAI epizootics in Asia and elsewhere, including HPAI H5N1) a matter of controversy. For a different, recently published opinion on the role of wild migratory waterbirds in the epizootic, see http://www.eaaflyway.net/wild-migratory-waterbirds-are-the-victims-of-bird-flu-not-the-cause/."

An updated information and map of the previous event (Kumamoto outbreak) is available at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_fup_0000015611_20140717_135701.pdf. Subscribers are also referred to FAO's current e-newsletter 104 titled "Avian influenza A(H5N8) detected in Europe... a journey to the West?" at http://www.fao.org/ag/againfo/resources/newsletter/2014_newsletter_104.html. - Mods.CRD/AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2955318,14930.]
